Steps to Push Code from VS Code to GitHub

Here’s a simple workflow you can note down and reuse whenever you want to push your Java programs from VS Code to GitHub.

One-time Setup

Install Git

Check with: git --version

If not installed, download from git-scm.com.

Configure Git (first time only)

git config --global user.name "YourName"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"

Regular Workflow

Initialize Git in your project folder

git init

Add your files

git add .

Commit your changes

git commit -m "Initial commit: LinearSearch program"

Link your local repo to GitHub

git remote add origin https://github.com/YourUsername/RepoName.git

Set branch name and push (first time)

git branch -M main
git push --set-upstream origin main

After Setup (Daily Use)

Make changes in VS Code.

Stage changes:

git add .

Commit changes:

git commit -m "Updated LinearSearch program"

Push changes:

git push

Optional Extras

Pull changes from GitHub (if you edit files online):

git pull

Create a new branch (for experiments):

git checkout -b new-feature
git push origin new-feature

This note gives you a clean checklist to follow every time you want to sync your VS Code project with GitHub.
